#: ../../03_Image_analysis/Intensity.md:38
msgid "**Saturation** Saturated pixels are so bright their intensity values max out our detector (camera). If you have saturated pixels in the cells you‚Äôre trying to measure, you really can‚Äôt do most intensity measurements. This is because for saturated pixels, you don‚Äôt know how bright they really are, just that they‚Äôre brighter than you can detect. There are some intensity measurements that are robust to some saturation. For example, the median intensity of an image won‚Äôt be affected by saturation unless you have >¬Ω the image saturated. But measurements like mean intensity will be affected by saturation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../03_Image_analysis/Intensity.md:40
msgid "**Inadequate controls** In most cases, the exact intensity measures you get don‚Äôt mean anything biologically in isolation. It‚Äôs only by comparison of conditions that we can generate some biological insight. A control condition is therefore **very** important to compare to your experimental condition."
msgstr ""

#: ../../03_Image_analysis/Intensity.md:42
msgid "**Not matching imaging conditions across experimental conditions** Because intensity measures are affected by exposure time, light source intensity, and other factors, it‚Äôs very important to match imaging settings across your samples. Relatedly, you should make sure you don‚Äôt separate imaging your experimental and control conditions to different days if this can be in any way avoided. Fluorophores can become dimmer over time in samples, which complicates interpretation if different sample types were imaged on different days."
